1
00:00:01,229 --> 00:00:19,929
Namo tassa bhagavato harahato sambha sambhudassa Namo tassa bhagavato harahato sambha sambhudassa

2
00:00:19,910 --> 00:00:36,673
Namo tassa bhagavato harahato samma sambodassam Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:36,694 --> 00:00:47,789
So, I'm continuing these little evening talks using Bhikkhu Bodhi's book, In the Buddha's Words, an anthology.

4
00:00:48,917 --> 00:00:53,683
And I thought to begin at the beginning, instead of going all over the place.

5
00:00:54,825 --> 00:00:58,930
And it starts off with what he calls a human condition.

6
00:01:01,973 --> 00:01:15,971
And, you know, when the Buddha came to his realization, he saw a sort of end to this suffering business.

7
00:01:17,216 --> 00:01:26,730
So if you can imagine a doctor, the sort of awkwardness of having to tell somebody they have a terminal illness and that there's no chance of it being healed.

8
00:01:27,691 --> 00:01:33,760
So, I mean, they might say, well, you might last nine months, one year, two years, but the news is really bad, you see.

9
00:01:34,341 --> 00:01:44,777
And it must be difficult, even if they've done it many times, to actually have to say that to somebody, knowing the shock and the horror that it causes in people.

10
00:01:46,224 --> 00:01:52,959
And it must be similar if somebody has a chronic illness, something like rheumatoid arthritis or something, or something like that.

11
00:01:53,700 --> 00:02:00,215
And they have to say to them, you know, we can't do anything about it, we can give you drugs and all that, but you're stuck with it.

12
00:02:01,618 --> 00:02:05,888
So again, it's like there's a despairing note about it and no help.

13
00:02:06,947 --> 00:02:15,120
Very different, of course, if the illness is something they can cure, then, you know, they're very happy to tell you that you'll be suffering miserably and terribly for a month.

14
00:02:15,139 --> 00:02:16,342
But at the end, you'll be all right.

15
00:02:17,323 --> 00:02:28,901
So when it comes to the harsh conditions of our life, the Buddha can be right in our face with it, you see, because he's got an answer.

16
00:02:29,542 --> 00:02:31,564
He says, well, there is an end to this suffering.

17
00:02:32,104 --> 00:02:35,250
So he can be fairly, you know, straight on the nose business.

18
00:02:36,343 --> 00:02:42,413
And these passages just tell you how he doesn't pull his punches, you see.

19
00:02:45,418 --> 00:02:47,600
He's talking here to King Pasenadi.

20
00:02:47,621 --> 00:02:51,165
So there were two areas where he wandered.

21
00:02:51,747 --> 00:02:54,812
He never really went over towards Bengal, towards Calcutta.

22
00:02:54,991 --> 00:03:02,824
He stayed within that area, Varanasi, Benares, present-day Benares, all the way up to where his people lived, the Sakyas.

23
00:03:03,225 --> 00:03:05,807
And he seems to have moved right over towards modern Delhi.

24
00:03:06,449 --> 00:03:09,010
So he wandered, you know, he wandered for quite a while.

25
00:03:09,032 --> 00:03:10,193
It was all over the place, really.

26
00:03:10,293 --> 00:03:12,775
He just kept walking.

27
00:03:12,794 --> 00:03:14,757
And there were two kings.

28
00:03:14,917 --> 00:03:21,483
One was Pasenadi, who was the ruler of the northern part of that area, the Gangetic plain.

29
00:03:22,123 --> 00:03:26,687
And there was Bimbisara in the south, who ruled the kingdom of Magadha.

30
00:03:27,229 --> 00:03:32,794
So Pasenadi, he must have known, even as a child, because his...

31
00:03:33,516 --> 00:03:37,200
his people, the Sakyas, would have been under that kingship.

32
00:03:37,341 --> 00:03:42,266
You often hear the tales of the Buddha being the prince of a great king and all that.

33
00:03:42,287 --> 00:03:48,533
But actually, it was a small tribe, the Sakyas, who lived on the borders of what is present-day Nepal.

34
00:03:49,395 --> 00:03:50,937
And his father was the head man.

35
00:03:50,956 --> 00:03:54,760
He was the chief and elective.

36
00:03:55,021 --> 00:03:57,183
It would have been a more democratic thing.

37
00:03:57,604 --> 00:03:59,727
Democratic only within that...

38
00:04:00,212 --> 00:04:05,259
within that caste, the Kshatriyas, the warrior caste, the rulers.

39
00:04:06,181 --> 00:04:10,026
And they came under the king of Kosala.

40
00:04:10,206 --> 00:04:14,233
The king of Kosala was their lord, you might say.

41
00:04:14,733 --> 00:04:15,835
Very feudal, you know.

42
00:04:16,615 --> 00:04:19,500
There's no record as to whether they paid duty or anything like that.

43
00:04:19,899 --> 00:04:21,302
But anyway, he obviously knows him.

44
00:04:21,322 --> 00:04:24,026
And King Pasenadi became a great supporter of his.

45
00:04:26,129 --> 00:04:28,211
So he's at the capital, Savatthi.

46
00:04:30,334 --> 00:04:37,045
And King Pasenadi of Kosala said to the Blessed One, Venerable Sir, is anyone who is born free from aging and death?

47
00:04:38,708 --> 00:04:39,769
He's obviously on his mind.

48
00:04:41,172 --> 00:04:44,838
Great King, no one who is born is free from aging and death.

49
00:04:45,579 --> 00:04:57,978
Even those affluent katiyas, so that's the ruling caste, rich with great wealth and property, with abundant gold and silver, abundant treasures and commodities, abundant wealth and grain,

50
00:04:58,464 --> 00:05:01,709
because they've been born, are not free from aging and death.

51
00:05:02,752 --> 00:05:12,507
Even those affluent Brahmins and those affluent householders with abundant wealth and grain, because they've been born, they're not free from aging and death.

52
00:05:13,608 --> 00:05:24,084
Even those monks who are Arahats, fully liberated, whose taints are destroyed, who've lived the holy life, done what has to be done, laid down the burdens,

53
00:05:25,009 --> 00:05:39,185
reached their own goal utterly destroyed the fetters of existence and are completely liberated through final knowledge even for them this body is subject to breaking up subject to being laid down see?

54
00:05:40,425 --> 00:05:53,699
so there's no even somebody who's fully liberated has to go through the horror now we know that for instance Moggallana who was the who was one of his two main disciples and he was known for his powers

55
00:05:54,507 --> 00:06:22,911
was seemingly murdered by bandits his other great disciple Sariputta seems to have died at home for peace Monday it would have been I think a sad thing for him that both of them died before he went when I was in Burma I saw a beautiful statue with the Buddha sitting and he had his hand pointing towards his heart like that you see so I'd never seen this mudra this

56
00:06:23,632 --> 00:06:25,475
What's the word for mudra?

57
00:06:27,036 --> 00:06:31,740
The position, you know, like you get them, well, like this one here, that's the samadhi posture.

58
00:06:32,742 --> 00:06:45,874
And they said to me it was a sadness he felt when he heard that the two teachers who had brought him so far were dead and he had wanted to pass on his message to them.

59
00:06:46,555 --> 00:06:52,240
So this tells us that, you know, sadness isn't beyond the Buddha.

60
00:06:52,725 --> 00:06:53,646
He's sad, you see.

61
00:06:53,966 --> 00:06:57,211
But he's not overwhelmed by it.

62
00:06:57,331 --> 00:07:01,235
He's not grieving for it.

63
00:07:01,255 --> 00:07:06,002
And there's a little phrase, there's a little verse that he creates.

64
00:07:06,682 --> 00:07:09,004
The beautiful chariots of kings wear out.

65
00:07:09,706 --> 00:07:12,769
This body too undergoes decay.

66
00:07:13,389 --> 00:07:15,833
But the dharma of the good does not decay.

67
00:07:16,434 --> 00:07:18,857
So the good proclaim along with the good.

68
00:07:20,619 --> 00:07:22,581
A little verse just to remind us that.

69
00:07:22,949 --> 00:07:24,872
The Dharma is beyond time.

70
00:07:25,132 --> 00:07:26,574
It's Akalika.

71
00:07:26,673 --> 00:07:34,586
One of the qualities of the Dharma that it exists as a law no matter what time or space you happen to be in.

72
00:07:36,869 --> 00:07:41,394
So then he goes on and this is quite a long little passage but we'll sort of get through it.

73
00:07:43,617 --> 00:07:52,550
So Asavati in the middle of the day King Pasenadi of Kosala approached the Blessed One paid homage to him and sat down to one side and the Blessed One then asked him

74
00:07:53,053 --> 00:08:22,572
now where have you come from great king in the middle of the day just now venerable sir I've been engaged in those affairs of kingship typical for kings who are intoxicated with the intoxication of sovereignty who are obsessed by greed for sensual pleasures and who've attained stable control of their country and who rule having conquered a great sphere of territory on earth it's funny intoxicated with the intoxication

75
00:08:22,855 --> 00:08:51,850
of sovereignty what do you think great king suppose a man would come to you from the east one who is trustworthy and reliable and would tell you for sure great king you should know this I'm coming from the east and there I saw a great mountain high as the clouds coming this way crushing all living beings do whatever you think should be done great king then a second man would come to you from the west and a third from the north and a fourth from the south

76
00:08:52,370 --> 00:08:56,735
one who is trustworthy and reliable and would tell you, for sure, great king, you should know this.

77
00:08:57,336 --> 00:09:03,865
I'm coming from the south, and then I saw a great mountain high as the clouds coming this way, crushing all living beings.

78
00:09:04,485 --> 00:09:06,307
Do whatever you think should be done, great king.

79
00:09:07,450 --> 00:09:15,860
If, great king, such a great peril should arise, such a terrible destruction of human life, the human state being so difficult to obtain, what should be done?

80
00:09:16,861 --> 00:09:22,308
Oh, if, venerable sir, such a great peril should arise, such a terrible destruction of human life,

81
00:09:22,727 --> 00:09:31,857
the human state being so difficult to obtain, what else should be done but to live by the Dharma, to live righteously and to do wholesome and meritorious deeds.

82
00:09:33,339 --> 00:09:39,125
I inform you, great king, I announce to you, great king, aging and death are rolling in on you.

83
00:09:40,346 --> 00:09:43,750
When aging and death are rolling in on you, great king, what should be done?

84
00:09:43,789 --> 00:09:52,278
As aging and death are rolling in on me, venerable sir, what else should be done but to live by the Dharma, to live righteously and to do

85
00:09:52,445 --> 00:09:54,447
wholesome and meritorious deeds.

86
00:09:57,068 --> 00:10:17,808
Venerable sir, kings intoxicated with the intoxication of sovereignty, obsessed by greed for sensual pleasures, who've attained stable control of their country and rule over a great sphere of territory, conquer by means of elephant battles, cavalry battles, chariot battles and infantry battles.

87
00:10:18,370 --> 00:10:21,793
But there is no hope of victory by such battles

88
00:10:22,076 --> 00:10:26,263
no chance of success when aging and death are rolling in.

89
00:10:27,465 --> 00:10:35,917
In this royal court, venerable sir, there are counselors who, when the enemies arrive, are capable of dividing them by subterfuge.

90
00:10:36,638 --> 00:10:44,269
There is no hope of victory by subterfuge, no chance of success when aging and death are rolling in.

91
00:10:45,711 --> 00:10:51,678
In this royal court, venerable sir, there exists abundant bullion and gold stored in vaults and lofts.

92
00:10:52,115 --> 00:10:56,399
And with such wealth we are capable of mollifying the enemies when they come.

93
00:10:57,041 --> 00:11:04,328
But there is no hope of victory by wealth, no chance of success when aging and death are rolling in.

94
00:11:05,571 --> 00:11:19,287
As aging and death are rolling in on me, Venerable Sir, what else should I do but to live by Dharma, live righteously and do wholesome and meritorious deeds?

95
00:11:19,773 --> 00:11:33,150
So it is, great king, so it is, great king, as aging and death are rolling in on you, what else should you do but live by Dharma, live righteously and do wholesome and meritorious deeds?

96
00:11:33,171 --> 00:11:34,932
This is what the Blessed One said.

97
00:11:37,797 --> 00:11:45,527
We can only hope that his words have some effect upon us and that we will live righteously and according to the Dharma.

98
00:11:46,485 --> 00:11:59,500
May you be fully liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later.

